<br>
You've just displayed colossal ignorance.<br>
<br>
You paid to enter the museum.  Is it your museum?<br>
<br>
You bought a ticket to a baseball game.  Do you own the seat?  Even for the course of the game?  If you misbehave, can they throw your ass out of the stadium, ticket or no ticket?<br>
<br>
You bought a house that's part of a condo association.  Can you just do what you want with it?  I bet the condo association rules, which are &quot;conditions&quot; of the purchase, don't let you paint that house purple.  I bet you can't add a third story, or use the house as a liquor store.  But hey, you bought it, you can do what you want with it, right?  Because it's your property?  <br>
<br>
More fundamentally, you didn't buy the art in question here.  You bought, repeat after me, &quot;A LIMITED LICENSE&quot; that allows you to do what the limited license says you can do, and nothing more.  This isn't a painting that you got to take home (and by the way, if the artist who sells you a painting wants to place a condition on the sale, that you can't display it at the Chicago Art Institute, that you can't deface it, that you can't use it as a party coaster, the artist is entitled to do that too .. if you don't like the condition, don't buy the art).  What you bought is the right to use the art in question.  And the contract of purchase, the terms and conditions that the artist spells out on the website, tells you how you can use it, and how you can't.  You didn't buy the right to use it however you wish.  If you want to negotiate for the right to do whatever you want with an artist's work, go ahead and try, but don't be surprised if the artist won't sell you the right to deface his work in any manner you see fit.  At least, unless you're prepared to pay him a LOT of money.  <br>
<br>
Apparently, you have no idea how the legal system related to property and licenses works in the United States.  You can express whatever opinions you like .. let's just all remember that they aren't educated opinions.  They're the world according to Garbhad, which has no relationship to the real world in which the rest of us have to live.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#242422><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub40.ezboard.com/bthesaryrntavern.showUserPublicProfile?gid=iyldaintingon>IyldainTingon</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style='color:pink;'>Tavern Floor Sweeper</span></span><br>  Posts: 8<br> <font color=#6FB8DD>(6/10/03 2:02 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub40.ezboard.com/fthesaryrntavernthefurnace.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3262.topic&index=288>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> bullshit Quirt</span><hr size=1> While a couple of your analogies may work, it doesn't apply here...to an extent.<br>
