<br>
As for the painting, if a term of the contract of sale was that you couldn't deface it, that term is binding.  Case in point, the colorization of films.  The original creators of the films tried to argue that it was a term of the original sale of the film that it couldn't be modified.  The difficulty was not that the term wasn't enforceable .. it's that the term wasn't explicit.  Nobody contemplated colorization, so everyone was reduced to arguing what the parties would have agreed to had they contemplated that possibility.  <br>
<br>
We don't have that problem here.  The artists contemplated exactly what could happen to their artwork, and they prohibited it.  They gave people access to the art, and gave them the right to use it, provided that they abided by certain explicit conditions.  As was said in that e-mail, they may be grateful for the cash contribution, but that doesn't give the contributor the right to ignore the conditions.  <br>
<br>
Hayley didn't buy the sig.  If she bought anything, she bought the right to use the sig, in the way that the artists explicitly allowed her to use the sig, and not in any other way.<br>
<br>
And whether Hayley is making any money on it is totally irrelevant.  <br>
<br>
The only real argument available is whether Hayley's use was &quot;fair use&quot; of the copyrighted material.  There are two questions here.  One is whether the doctrine of &quot;fair use&quot; can apply when the artist explicitly prohibits certain uses, and you agree to the prohibition (that dratted &quot;I Agree&quot; button again).  I don't think the doctrine can apply, under those circumstances.  The other question is whether Hayley's use was in fact a &quot;fair use&quot;.  Typically, the &quot;fair use&quot; doctrine only applies when you use a small amount of the original copyrighted material, and only when you attribute the material to the copyright holder (otherwise it's plagiarism).  Hayley's sig failed on both counts, until she added the attribution, but I still think it's too large a chunk of the original material to constitute a &quot;fair use&quot;.<br>
<br>
So where does that leave us?  I think &quot;fair use&quot; is a losing argument, I don't even think it's close, but at least it isn't absurd on its face.  Unlike the &quot;I bought it, I'll do with it as I damn well please&quot; argument, which would get you laughed at and/or slapped with punitive damages.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub40.ezboard.com/bthesaryrntavern.showUserPublicProfile?gid=garbhad>Garbhad</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/misc_2.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I will not<br>celebrate<br>
