<br>
Ever hear of easements?  They are conditions attached to the deed that tell you what you can and cannot do with that house of yours, whatever you paid for it.  The subject of easements is only several hundreds of years old.  Not every piece of real estate is subject to easements, but many are.  <br>
<br>
I used to own a 10-acre parcel of land that abutted a wildlife refuge.  Sometime in the distant past, someone had granted an easement on that parcel that prevented any future owner from building except in one small corner of the parcel, far away from the wildlife refuge.  Was that easement enforceable?  Damn straight it was.  It was a condition of the purchase, I knew it before I bought the land, and basically I was stuck with that condition.  Just like Hayley, I had two choices.  Live with the condition, or choose not to make the purchase.  <br>
<br>
And of course the government can tell you what you can and cannot do.  It will be happy to tell you not to burn trash in your yard, not to cut down trees with a diameter greater than 18 inches, not to water the lawn more than 3 days a week, and not to have more than 6 visitors per day (yes, Virginia, there are laws like that, they are designed to prevent you from turning your residence into a place of business). <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#242422><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub40.ezboard.com/bthesaryrntavern.showUserPublicProfile?gid=garbhad>Garbhad</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/misc_2.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I will not<br>celebrate<br>
