<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>So she Frankendolled them to steal someones term. She DID pay for it.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
No, and there is the fatal flaw in the &quot;She did nothing wrong&quot; arguement.  She bought nothing.  She donated to a community.  She did not purchase any image(s) or the editing rights to those images.  There was no free Extra Large Pullover Fleece with donation.<br>
<br>
Lets say you go to an art house.  Instead of charging admission the art house instead has a donation box at the exit.  Lets go a step further and say the art house also has stacks of reproductions next to each painting with a sign saying &quot;Take one and proudly display.  But the artist requests that you do not alter this image and that you give him/her proper credit.  Sign here if you agree.&quot;  You grab a black and white reproduction of one painting that catches your eye and sign the form.  While leaving(or two days later after your guilt gets the better of you), you drop $40 in the donation box.  Being creative, you get the idea to get out your crayolas and make the black and white a colorful creation.  You then have that colored image made into a big billboard with your name in lights and put it up on a busy street in the artists home town.<br>
<br>
You have not broken a single criminal law.  But the artist could sue you to have the image removed and he would win unless you could prove your creation was a satire or a parody.  If you put up the same billboard with the artists name in lights then he would have no case to sue and would probably thank you.  Because he made an act of sale(the sign saying please take one) and you abided by the terms of that sale.<br>
<br>
What monetary value could he sue you for since you made no money on the sign?  Damages come in two basic forms in law suits 1)compensatory - meant to compensate for some loss caused and 2)punitive - meant to punish the offending party as an encouragement for them not to repeat the action.<br>
<br>
That is the exact situation we have here except on an incredibly small scale.  The donation doesnt matter because there was no implied purchase or sale of alteration rights.  The alteration matters because the artists in question made it clear they did not want there images altered.  The lack of credit matters because the artists requested proper credit if their images were used.  <br>
<br>
And none of this matters because she has now removed the image and Im assuming the wronged parties are now happy and not planning a multi-billion dollar law suit.  It happened exactly like it was supposed to happen.  The BF was the forum instead of a court.  We all here were the jury.  Both sides made arguements.  The Doll Team convinced the VD team that they were wrong and they reached an out of court settlement(removal of the sig).  <br>
<br>
So now we can debate amongst ourselves the details of the trial.  Outcome was decided with our help if not with our legal decree.  I promise that sig would still be up, and that $40 would still be in Hayleys bank account if court of opinion hadnt stepped in.  <br>
<br>
So, offending sig gone.  PA gets a $40 donation through guilt.  Hayley's rep gets further tarnished(can rust tarnish?).  Good work citizens.  Case dismissed...........until next time. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub40.ezboard.com/bthesaryrntavern.showUserPublicProfile?gid=bygzalf>Bygzalf</A> at: 6/10/03 3:25 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#242422><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub40.ezboard.com/bthesaryrntavern.showUserPublicProfile?gid=garbhad>Garbhad</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/misc_2.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I will not<br>celebrate<br>
